On Friday, the rabbit headed left on the road. The rabbit would feel the many eyes of the forest turn their gaze upon it, with each minor movement tracked by a hundred eyes that judged it, yet the rabbit kept hopping along. Heading left down the road, the forest would be set in a lightless blaze as trees and grass turned to ash around the rabbit, while it could feel its blood boil and flesh cook, yet the rabbit kept hopping along. The rabbit then took a right down the path leading to lands filled with bear traps and pits. The rabbit could hear the sounds of a fox behind it, chasing it down. Once the fox caught the rabbit, it drove its teeth deep into its leg, yet the rabbit kept hopping along.

On Saturday, the rabbit went down the right road. After traveling far enough, the rabbit stumbled into a spider's web. The web would wrap around the rabbit's limbs as a spider above grabbed and pulled at the web like strings, and the spider would force the rabbit to keep hopping along. No longer in control of its own legs, the rabbit would head down the left path. Slowly, the world around it would shrivel and die as the sky would be coated in a thin layer of green fog. As the flesh would start to fall off the rabbit's bones, it was forced further along. Forced to the right, the rabbit would finally find itself at the end of the path, with the world falling beneath it. The rabbit’s little body would give out, falling to the ground so not even the spider could force the rabbit any further along.

On Monday, the rabbit found itself heading left down the path. As the path continues, the world slowly closes around the rabbit till its lungs are crushed and ground to dust by the dirt that has now surrounded it, yet the rabbit keeps hopping along. Eventually, the world lets up, and the rabbit keeps hopping along. As it travels, it takes the middle road till the sky above goes black, and all light is stripped from the rabbit’s eyes, yet the rabbit keeps hopping along.

On Thursday, the rabbit returned to the middle road. For the first time on its journey, the rabbit was joined by others that looked just like it. The further the rabbit went down the road, the more that joined it with each one more wrong than the ones before, with their eyes in the wrong place, their legs too long, or their ears too wide as they asked the rabbit to join them, but the rabbit kept hopping along. The rabbit continued down the middle road till the dirt turned to muscle and bone that pulsed with each hop it took. Slowly, blood vessels would work their way out of the muscle and wrap around the rabbit's legs, attempting to pull them from its body, yet the rabbit kept hopping along.

On Tuesday, the rabbit found itself heading right down the path. Slowly, the path heads into a marsh where the bugs skitter and crawl their way into the rabbit’s ears and under its eyes, where they may lay their eggs, yet the rabbit keeps hopping along. Continuing down the right path, the rabbit found itself in a silent and empty forest with nothing but the sound of its own breath to keep it company, yet the rabbit kept hopping along. Keeping to the right side, the rabbit found the path spinning in on itself, and with each hop the rabbit could feel its body shift and change till the rabbit couldn’t even tell if it was the same rabbit that had first started down the path, yet the rabbit kept hopping along.

files.name: Report #100719-AT
files.insides:
Report #100719-AT
Date 7-12-21
“Field Mission #0172”

I feel the need to address some disclaimers before I write this report. Firstly, this was our first field mission since the Covid 19 shutdown. There are things in this report that go to show just how rusty we were after being stuck inside for almost two years. Secondly, we departed later from the facility than first advised by Mr. ▮▮▮▮ as the 12th of July was the hottest day recorded that year and the abandoned radio station building off of MO Highway 11 was in the middle of an uncovered field. Third, ▮▮▮▮ is still in the hospital after the mission. We have been advised to take some days off to deal with it but I had to get this all down as soon as possible. I apologize if it seems rushed.

At 13:00 hours, members of the Acquisitions Team departed from the collection facility to an address given. We arrived at approximately 13:30 hours to an abandoned radio station. It appeared from the outside to have not had much use in the past 50 years, give or take. It was a fairly small building and must have been used for only small town radio. The satellite dish on the top was small- too small to reach anything farther than the span of Kirksville. Someone on the team decided to switch the FM frequency in ▮▮▮▮ truck to the one that matched the giant sign on the outside. None of us remember it now and we didn't write it down. We were met with a gospel reading priest who was going on about damnation. It appeared as if the frequency of this station had been given to some local baptist church.

The outside had been boarded up with scrap wood. It covered most of the windows and all the doors. Painted on in great letters all around was KIRKSVILLE POLICE - TRESSPASSERS WILL BE PROSECUTED TO THE FULLEST EXTENT OF THE LAW. Some of the boards had already been moved and the evidence inside pointed to local college students getting drunk in old abandoned places. We were only a couple miles away from Truman State University. Mr. Zelenski had recently bought the place out so ▮▮▮▮ grabbed a crowbar out of the bed of his truck and got to work on them, not caring much about the “law”.

The lights were still not working. The sale of the property had only just gone through and even if the power was turned back on by the power company, the wiring would probably set the entire place ablaze. ▮▮▮▮ took down the rest of the boards with his crowbar while the rest of us looked around, hoping to bring in some light.

Arrest Record of Isaac Hartwell
Date: ▮▮/▮▮/▮▮
Time: 09:30
Arresting Officer: SGT. Mason Wells
On ▮▮▮▮▮▮▮▮ a 911 call was made from the Levittown Public Library about a violent individual. When SGT Wells and Officer James arrived on the scene, Isaac Hartwell had already injured 3 bystanders with a crowbar. Isaac had charged at the Officers, managing to strike James and break his ribcage before being shot by SGT Wells. After being taken for treatment from the gunshot wounds, Isaac Hartwell was taken to the Levittown Detention Department.
